,Recommended,297720,22258495,"Posted: 5 April, 2016",all,(-C-)Fjonan,"I'd call it a narrative experiment that takes inspirations by recent science-fiction movies like ""Moon"" or ""Interstellar"" with a more passive ""walking simulator"" approach with a good amount of platforming in the mix when moving around. I loved what it tries story wise even if it in my opinion lacks a good amount of polish which I think stems from the small team that really tried to get a lot in. But that is also one of the main problems I had with the game: it could have been half as long. Getting from one objective to the other gets tedious and does not further the feeling of loneliness but being in a game ticking boxes. It pains me to think that so much energy was used to make the game larger, when the opposite would have made it that much more focused.But even with all it shortcomings I can appreciate the core concept of what it is trying to convey. It touches on many topics, some on the sidelines, some major (the holo-messages were relly moving) and it shines through that the game is trying more than it ultimately can handle. I would love to read some interpretations on the story in the forums (which I will not mention here because of spoilers) and I want the developers to keep going in this direction and get better at it, because this kind of game is still uncommon and I like it for it.If you like new experiences in games and if you have no problems with an indie diamond-in-the-rough I reccomend taking a look. This, for me, is an example that shows that games can be much more than mere mechanics tied together by a cheesy story you don't care about."
