,Not Recommended,297720,23720031,"Posted: 22 June, 2016",all,Soren1015,"I really don't want to bash this game too much as whoever made it has a great deal of potential, so instead I'll offer up my criticisms keep in mind these are meant in a constructive manner.[This has spoilers]Ok so first off the premise of waking up over and over again on varying worlds with no real sense of time or place is excellent, as is the Main Character's slow realization that what was important was their family. I mark those as both things the game does well.Unfortunately we get into the things the game does not do so well. (Note: the following do not apply to the game's final level I will have a seperate point about that.)* Transversing the various worlds.- I like that each world has its own theme and what not but they get so vast that it quickly becomes an exceedingly boring platformer that boils down to ""go hear using the tool this level gave you"" I think the worst part is the levels were just made too large for the number of them the game tries to fit and they end up being very bland.* The bonus objectives - The bonus objectives more often than not would frankly not be worth the time it would take to reach them. Most of the time you would get a tiny item of day to day life from the MC's past that would not be visible to the AVA unit traveling with you. Now while a little homesick delusion adds a nice surreal touch that I do approve of I found these to just not be worth the sometimes several minutes of detour to reach them. HOWEVER every now and then one of the bonus items would be something completely off the wall and insane such as the Chris Rock rock. Items as crazy as that were definately worth the extra journey and I cite them as an example of something unexpected the game does well.*The AVA unit that tags around through your levels. The design and voice acting on the unit are excellent however with the exception of the final level this too became bland and repetitive as the character was never really noticably different from one level to the next. I felt that if the AVA unit had some transformation of personality similar to the way the MC's personality changes from level to level this would have been a large improvement.TLDR: The game has a good premise and a solid control scheme but suffers from blandness.Now onto the game's greatest aspect... its FINAL level!The final level of the game. The final level was... an astonishment. By this point the blandness of the past few levels (ESPECIALLY the Molten World level) had pushed me to a point where I just wanted the game to end as soon as possible, the Chris Rock rock was amazing but points of that quality were too few and TOO far between. Then came the last level. The last level was like a merciful breath of air after drowning in dullness. The last level is VASTLY superior to the rest of the game. It still has a bland world you are moving through HOWEVER you do not notice as the goals are so rewarding. The AVA unit gets ALL the personality it could have had over the course of the game in this one level and is highly entertaining. The points you travel to in the last level go from mundane to insane in an amazing way. The last level is the journey from normal to surreal that I wanted to experiance over the course of the whole game, packed into one level. The final level is the reason I chose to write the review for this game. It was almost worth slogging through the previous bland dragging parts of the game JUST for the pleasure of going through the last level.TLDR: The last level is the journey from normal to surreal, as the MC slips into madness, that I wanted from this game all along. It is the game's greatest redeeming feature.The last level proves that this developer has potential and I would look forward to their future work once they refine that potential. However I cannot recommend this game just on the last level."
76561198018340366,Recommended,297720,19689595,"Posted: 13 December, 2015",all,EmmaEchoic,"FIrst of all I can only recommend this game if it's extremely on sale. I got this for two dollars, and having played it I think it's a fair price for at least five.My favorite part of this game is just the exploration, travelling through unknown planets that look awesome yet have very real dangers. It was super immersive......that is when it worked. I had a handful of frustrating moments when I would clip through the floor to my death or get caught in a graphics hole. When I play these games though I understand how difficult it is for a small team to program a 3D game like this, and that you just have to accept glitches like that.The story was interesting enough to keep me going to find out what happens nexts but it was just underwhelming. The game beats you over the the head with the ""REMEMBER YOUR FAMILY!?!?!"" shtick in a very ham-fisted fashion. The voice acting from all the family members was poor and unbelievable. Also I'm ninety percent sure that the plot of this game was doing that "" I'm purposely vague and abstract so I can pretend I'm being profound and meaningful"" sort of thing. I realized halfway that all these weird plot points I was finding were just pointless BS, and it was pretty disappointing. Was the astronaut dead the whole time? Was he picked up and died in a hospital later? Was he just stranded on the planet? Is this all just a dream or a coma fantasy? Who knows, I don't even think the devs did tbh.A.V.A., your robot companion, was a fantastic character though. Watching her slowly change over each sequence was really awesome. Her dialogue, while not really having a point a lot of the time, was meaninful in characterizing her as a sentient being going through an existential crisis.So if you like jumping around weird abstract planets in low gravity with  jetpack, you should buy this game. Just don't go into it expecting a deep plot or any sort of clarification or closure on what's going on."
