76561198007273600,Recommended,297720,18223017,"Posted: 27 September, 2015",all,Syt1976,"SPOILER FREEIntroI picked this up based on Jesse Cox's video on it - it was an intriguing premise and I was very curious to see what was going on within the game's story.As it states in the game's News/Updates, this isn't a game for everyone. It's an interactive story, a narrative museum or, as the common term these days is, a ""walking simulator,"" in that its focus is on story and creating a certain atmosphere to create a narrative experience with limited gameplay mechanics. That said, the game has a few (easy) jumping puzzles, and a few times I had to spend some time figuring out the path to my next objective. If this isn't something you like, then skip it.If you enjoy games of this type and a sci-fi plot and alien worlds, then you may want to give this a look.Graphics/Controls/PresentationAs said, the gameplay mechanics are relatively simple. Walking, sprinting, interacting. Later on you will also make use of a jetpack. The controls were absolutely fine. I'm not a twitch gamer and I managed fine.The game's design is very neat, with lots of detail in your little home base (most of it not interactive). The alien worlds are also each unique in their own way and offer a variety of different environments. Each planet seems very large, though I'm uncertain if there's much point to deviating from your objectives too much.The graphics quality was good on my GTX770Ti. On planets you will find that there's many decorative objects through which you can clip, and some through which you don't - you will learn which is which. Occasionally walls glitch a bit. Unfortunately, there's a fair amount of environmental pop in and even at maximum the view distance seemed a bit short, and on a few occasions I was left wondering if a certain direction would be navigable because I couldn't see if there would be solid ground, a cliff, a ramp etc. I think I would have preferred some fog to obscure the pop in, and perhaps low res models for far off environments to make navigation easier.Story and Game PlayThe game sets up an intriguing mystery within the first half hour that drew me in rather effectively and provided the motivation to continue playing. While progressing I spun several theories in my head as to where the story was leading. However, I found that by mid-game it was pretty clear, despite a few doubts in the back of my brain.Most of the gameplay has you chasing objectives on the planet surface, having to figure out how to get there and avoiding obstacles. You can die, but the consequences aren't severe. When you get a new objective, always check if there's a ""secondary"" in your HUD and check that one, too, to get the full story. Unfortunately, after the original WTF-factor of some of the things you encounter, some of the things you see will become a bit mundane.The voice acting was a very nice touch, and in the last chapter I had quite a few laughs. The main character is silent except for on screen text. Some of the text disappears quickly, and sometimes it's so long it obscures a fair part of the screen. I wish there had been a different solution for this. Your little companion drone AVA is fairly fleshed out and undergoes her own little character arc.The game is fairly introspective and in a few ways hit close to home for me. The resolution was IMHO slightly weak. I obviously don't want to spoilt it, but I was more left wondering, how the end would be presented and not what would happen. In hindsight the game functions as a parabel on ... a few topics; again no spoilers.Final ThoughtsI finished the game in 5 hours. As with most games in its genre there's little replay value, unless you want to see if you missed any secondary objectives. €15.- may seem a bit steep for that. I don't regret the purchase (it's cheaper than going to the movies), but I can see why people interested in this game may want to wait for a sale."
