76561198124457598,Recommended,297720,19981614,"Posted: 26 December, 2015",all,CountDog,"Corpse of Discovery a weird sci fi fictional plat forming intense game. Playing in between 3-4 hours. The game, quality explodes my expectations, when first launching the game you get an eerie feeling that whatever happens  when you decide to hit the new game words, displayed on the menu. It's going to be a first person narrative story! Oh I wonder How I knew that?When first entering the mind of an astronaut that had just momentarily awakened. The environment around you appears to be a base of some sort. I hadn't been certain whether I was on aboard a ship,  land base maybe? upon further expectation you discover in first person objects around your bedroom that relates to the time you had spent on earth, now in control of a character who is nameless as far as I can tell? You begin to walk around the exterior, doors will separate you from other rooms. I won’t go into detail as what is in each room, but I do suggest you re observe everything you’ve already interacted with as you progress this solemn tale.Through the story you’l find your self traversing planets with epic environments that range from a desert, flora and fauna filled, and some with life forms of all kinds yet to be named, as well discovered. I never found myself being bored once I began to explore a planet.  A little circle bot will accompany you for every planet you are on, giving you reassurance of the terrific work your performing, that few humans will ever carry the likeliness that you will one day bring back to earth. The bot itself also records data of you and the planet you are on, eventually relaying the information back to the company you work for. I don’t want to get into details for the story, I will say it’s easily the strongest trait for this particular title.Plat forming, a huge part in Corpse of Discovery, you’ll find yourself avoiding and planning routes ahead as some objectives require you to travel to high mountain areas that at first look impossible to explore till your actually at the base of the it. Your given a small jet pack like boost to help you plan your jumps accordingly. Again I don’t want to spoil anything for you, but there will be moments where your deciding how your going to go about this planet, just by looking ahead of you. I’ll argue that’s about as game play as it gets, some planets offer different resistances of gravity, allowing you to enjoy some higher jumps, which can be satisfying as you’ll notice for various reasons I can’t go into.You find yourself accompanied by much dialog, as well many different types of “feeling” music, is the only way I can think of how to describe that right now. Some of it evokes feeling that make you feel like your an alien on another planet, horror, sadness, anger, so much is great with this sound track, if I had to complain about one factor I had noticed with my play through, that periodically the music would cut off without reason destroying some of the immersion I had settled in myself at that point. Now that im on that topic, you as a player of discovery, will notice some glitches. I found nothing game breaking, but they are there, I hope you don’t find anything, but be forewarned!I wish I had more to say, but really you should just buy this game, it’s slow, plays with your emotions, and delivers a fantastic ending that will spin your head around for the next couple of hours. I hope these dev’s keep up the quality they delivered in this walking, jumping discovery game, which I always recommend to people around me. I paid $1.50 for this on a sale it had, but I would gladly fork over another $10.00.  Good day!"
