,Recommended,297720,20827126,"Posted: 29 January, 2016",all,Ephiraal,"Hey, a walking simulator that doesn't suck!In many ways, Corpse of Discovery reminds me of Soma, yes, that Soma. The horror game from Frictional Games that involves lots of walking from A to B while ocassionally listening (and conversing with, in Soma anyway) with a female A.I. who is also the driving force behind your objectives. As you try to reach these objectives, you will encounter monsters (I'm not very comfortable calling them monsters in either game) that may hinder you in making immediate progress.The dividing line between these two games is that Corpse of Discovery is made on a budget, while Soma has a triple-A polish fitting any effort by giants like EA or Ubisoft. When I say that Corpse of Discovery is made on a budget, I mean it looks like a decent 360 title circa 2008-2010 but with some added annoyances. Some of the flora you'll encounter in the game, as solid as they might seem, can be clipped through. Same goes for ankle/knee high-ish rocks. This is a bit frustrating as it gives the game an air of being unfinished, though not gamebreaking.In terms of setting, story, and gameplay, the game excels in the two former and does precisely what it should do with the latter. Being a walking simulator, by default the game sports somewhat rudimentary mechanics; you walk, sprint, jump, and activate stuff and that is it. Setting is... everchanging and has some fantastical imagery to show you. Story is also very interesting and plays around with family as a theme, which is a direct contrast to what the game is. It's interesting to say the least.If you can ignore the graphical and technical shortcomings of the game, Corpse of Discovery is an engrossing sci-fi adventure that sucks you in and demands your attention. Being relatively cheap is also plus for the game, so that is worth keeping in mind. All in all, I cannot recommend Corpse of Discovery enough, even despite its budgetary limitations."
