76561198067498569,Recommended,297720,23637632,"Posted: 18 June, 2016",all,Reozul,"The biggest problem I have with this game is the blatant spoiler its title and art represents.For its pricetag, the game is very well made and aside from a few ""texture hovering above actual ground"" problems at the start of the 5th mission, I couldn't find any mechanical fault with it.Movement controls work exceedingly well except for a bit of an issue with vertical movement in mission 4 due to lower gravity (rapid ascent makes finicky moveemnt a bit twitch-based).The story is sufficiently surreal to match the visuals and if it were not for my first sentence up there would possibly leave the player guessing for a bit.Though in some respects the story may be a bit too confusing and lacking internal consistency. That may be the point but quickly got me to the point where their apparent lack of such internal logic or explainability made me stop caring about them.Overall I can truly recommend this game. My playthrough took not quite 4 hours in total and was a fun time.The closts game to this in general tone I can think of (for reference) would be ""lifeless planet"".This game is not as polished as that, but stil presents quite a bit of the same explorational feel."
76561198054995351,Recommended,297720,23009159,"Posted: 15 May, 2016",all,Lucas McCain,"Interesting game. The platforming is fun, if not particularly challenging. The environments are strange and varied enough. Some of the odd things you find along the way are amusing. Most of the voiceacting is quite good. All in all this is a decent title. I'm not blown away by it, but it held my interest pretty well for the amount of time it took to complete it."
76561198087530744,Recommended,297720,26004740,"Posted: 12 October, 2016",all,Macedonica,"Corpse of Discovery is a game which sees you re-awaken time and again as an astronaut/explorer aided by an EVA unit and tasked to mark or discover various items. Each time you wake up things have shifted and your environment has changed. EVA is droll and satirical in her attempts to motivate you. It is on one level a surreal moebius loop and on another a dark dystopian nightmare.In terms of gameplay, this is nothing more than travelling to locations on each new planet and interacting with each find at that location. This is spiced up with the addition of a jet pack and platforming elements which bring in a nice verticality to the usual 'walking simulator' mechanic. Let me say, that the planet environments are gorgeous in a No Man Sky style (although this games obviously predates that 'game'). It is a joy to jet-pack through some of the later planets.Simple game-play aside, Corpse of Discovery unsettles you as the loops unravel and unwind and a darker narrative emerges. Satire and absurdity combine with chilling mood music and the lovely droll tones of EVA's voice to really unsettle you. As for the ending - as with all good philisophical sci-fi, it leaves you adrift a little and throws the meaning into your own hands.This worked for me - others will find it simplistic or perhaps a cop-out. I enjoyed this game - especially after the decale of NMS. Yes, it is short but in terms of mood and atmosphere, it works."
,Recommended,297720,24201006,"Posted: 9 July, 2016",all,Frosty Grin,"Walking simulator... with jetpacks! A fresh, interesting twist. Beautiful graphics, nice music, touching story with good voice acting and a bit of humor. The amount of challenge is just right and jetpacking feels good - which is an achievement. No technical issues in my experience. One thing that was a little unexpected is that the game is quite demanding - a card like the R9 380 is barely enough for high settings. Overall, very pleasant experience."
